Text.Value: Not every threat to Faer√ªn resides there. Better to prevent a catastrophe than to face it. Even if it means a Hellhunt.
Keep out of my mind. I told you - the eye's a rock, nothing more. And that's the end of it.
*Your mind is full, bursting with ecstasy and terror. Finally, it is coming. You are becoming.*
*You find only darkness. Wyll's thoughts are closed to you.*
Enter his mind. What isn't he telling you?
Enter his mind. What isn't he telling you?
The Blade doesn't just stick to the frontiers though, does he?
After my exile, I was hunting near the Cloakwood. I heard a child crying out from a lone farmstead.
The helpless, though - they need the light of others. They're the ones who seek out the Blade.
*Something stirs deep within you, hungry and alert... it's taking something you'll never get back.*
*Tiny grooves spider across the eye's surface. It resembles a sending stone, used to confer with distant contacts.*
I shouldn't be surprised. You are a great talent - when darkness falls, you make your own light.
*His breathing quickens; his jaw tenses. Wyll is keeping something from you.*
Leave.
All right.
I can only leave the rest to your imagination. Suffice to say, I hunt monsters - devils included. And I will do what I can to quench the Coast of their flames.
Having a worm wriggling in my skull didn't instil much confidence in the days ahead.
A powerful friend with a keen interest in... privacy. I'm sworn to say no more.
Whatever became of the boy, I wonder?
Baldur's Gate, born and raised. The only son of a single father.
Angry at the monsters preying on innocents. Angry at the so-called good gods, for tolerating the cruelty of the evil.
She fled from my reach - even climbed aboard the mind flayer ship as it screeched through the Hells. I followed in close pursuit.
I was hunting near the Cloakwood when I heard it - a child crying out from a lone farmstead.
Keep out of my mind. I told you - the eye's a rock, nothing more.
You disavowed me of that notion soon enough.
Leave.
It makes me angry to think about, still.

EditorData.logicalname: Still in act 1, Mizora judgment hasn't happened

Text.Value: *You watch and listen for signs of deceit, but sense nothing unusual.*
Draw on the power within to enforce your will.
Is that how you lost your eye - in the goblin battle?
I thought you were an archdevil's servant come to bathe the frontiers in flame.
The frontiers demanded a blade. And so I heeded.
Proud? No. Angry.
*A shiver runs across your mind... you feel sated.*

RuleGroup.RuleString: CLERIC or SORCERER or WARLOCK or WIZARD

Text.Value: Lean in and examine the eye more closely.
No. But he named me friend, and that meant the world.
How great could you be? I've never heard of you.
*The presence deep in your mind is awake, unblinking. This is it. A single word pervades your consciousness: 'Soon'.*
My father once said, 'One does not pursue a champion's life. One merely answers its call.'
All right, then. Let's change the subject.
I'd like to talk about something else.
Draw on the power within to enforce your will.
One of the archdevil Zariel's own - chaos incarnate, a devil with pure fire for a heart. I made my way to Avernus to stop her.
In the boy's tears, I finally saw the suffering wrought by the villains of the wild.
I don't remember much of the battle. But I remember drying the boy's tears after.
Goblins? Pitiful vermin, easy to kill - hardly worth getting worked up about.
It's not exactly easy to journey to the Hells from the Sword Coast. How did you manage it?
Ah, but that is a story reserved for lifetime friends and calmer days.
A most vicious one, in fact.
Who is this 'source' of yours?
It's nice to finally put a face to the name.
*Beyond the voice you find only shadow - a piece of Wyll's mind locked away from intruders.*
I found him in the fields, flanked by goblins. His mother's corpse bled into the soil next to him.
Isn't your eye a sending stone?
So it was for me.
Tell that to the boy shivering over his mother's ravaged corpse.
Yet you were chasing a devil in the Hells. How did that come about?
I can't bear to imagine the lives Karlach might be taking, the damage she might be doing.
A classic drama, a staunch father and his rebellious son. Better heard from the bards' lips than mine.
*Your right eye vibrates and a woman's voice echoes in your head. 'I've a sweet tooth, and devil's on the menu.'*
A - sending stone? Nothing so special, I assure you.
By all means.
*A shadow swims across your vision, and a familiar voice tells you to be calm. You are loved.*
You are a warlock. You know about bound souls and frozen tongues.
But what of the others? The children never saved, the cries never heard?
What are you...

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Wyll is surprised - the player is intruding on his mind.

Text.Value: What act could be finer than saving a life? You must have felt proud.
I left him with his uncles. Five years on, and he's flourishing. If only every child were so lucky.
And it's nice to meet someone of your talents.
And he named you the Blade of Frontiers?
I mourn the ones I could never save, whose cries I never heard.
A powerful friend, hm? Like a warlock patron, perhaps?
Leave.
*Your mind lurches, reeling suddenly as if... bitten.*
It's made from pure Bloodstone, carved from the Galena Mountains just north of the Moonsea. A reminder that sometimes, blood must be shed and sacrifices must be made.
Karlach's fires raged in Baldur's Gate before she escaped to Avernus, as my source told it - and she was planning to return.
*Your blood runs quicker, feeding the gnawing absence at the centre of your mind.*
And before that?

EditorData.logicalname: If player doesn't know Ravengard is father

Text.Value: Let's move on to other matters.
Gladly.
It was an even bloodier day and a stronger foe.
He wanted one life for me; I chose another. We haven't spoken since I left the city.
With you as my ally, the future looks a little less daunting.
*A strange sensation courses through you, and your companion's mind unfolds, secrets half-revealed.*
*You focus on the source of the power, but it is quiet and still. It needs to rest.*
Angry at myself that it took so long for me to see the Coast's suffering.

Synopsis: Default dialogue when speaking to Wyll during exploration.
